Clarification: setup_windows_scheduler.ps1 vs topic content
setup_windows_scheduler.ps1 only registers the Windows scheduled task that runs daily_commit_scheduler.ps1 (daily commits). It does not create topic folders or README/code.

Topic creation and all “filled” content are handled by add_new_topic.ps1. A short comment was added at the top of setup_windows_scheduler.ps1 so that’s obvious.

What we automated in add_new_topic.ps1
When there is no folder automation_1\presets\<topic>\, the script now generates full default content (not empty placeholders):

README.md — Sections for definition, characteristics, operations, complexity table skeleton, patterns, interview problems (easy/medium/hard), learning path, and pointers to the Java/Python files.
PRACTICE_PROBLEMS.md — Structured problem list with instructions, pattern sections, and interview tips (all with {0} filled from the topic name).
python/01_basics.py — Runnable {Topic}Basics class with describe(), checklist(), and main().
java/...Basics.java — Same idea: describe(), checklist(), main().
Presets still win: if presets\stack\ (or another topic) exists, that bundle is copied in full, same as before.

Java compile fix
PowerShell’s Out-File -Encoding UTF8 adds a BOM, which javac rejects. Java and Python starters are now written with Write-Utf8NoBom (UTF-8, no BOM).

